<div class="{{ name }}-demo panel">
    <div class="panel-title">
        <h6>Inline Inputs</h6>
    </div>
    <div class="tablet-two columns panel-content">
        <div class="example">
            <p>This is a paragraph demonstrating the use of a <input type="text" placeholder="text field" /> and a <input type="password" placeholder="password field" /> inline with text. Even <label for="inline-radio-1"><input type="radio" id="inline-radio-1" name="inline-radio"> Radio Button 1</label> <label for="inline-radio-2"><input type="radio" id="inline-radio-2" name="inline-radio"> Radio Button 2</label> or a <label for="inline-checkbox"><input type="checkbox" id="inline-checkbox"> Checkbox</label> can also be used. Also a basic select 
                <select class="native">
                    <option>Native Select</option>
                    <option>Native Select 1</option>
                    <option>Native Select 2</option>
                    <option>Native Select 3</option>
                </select>
                 or an 
                <select>
                    <option>Skinned Select</option>
                    <option>Skinned Select 1</option>
                    <option>Skinned Select 2</option>
                    <option>Skinned Select 3</option>
                </select> 
            can be placed inline with text. By default inline inputs inherit the line-height of the container.</p>

            <p>Although html5 input elements are not yet widely supported we can still use them inline and maintain the vertical rythm. For example a color input <input type="color"> or a date input <input type="date" >. A date time input <input type="datetime"> corrected for a local timezone <input type="datetime-local">. Also emails <input type="email" placeholder="email"> or numbers <input type="number">. Even a range picker <input type="range">. You can put a search field <input type="search"> or a phone <input type="tel"> or a url input <input type="url" >. There's also the super cool time input <input type="time">, month <input type="month" > and week input <input type="week">.</p>
